rk  ), but in the absence of any medieval evidence this is highly conjectural.","Altered form of German   Starke  , written thus to preserve the second syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Starkes","meanings":["English (Hampshire and Sussex):","probably a variant of   Starkey  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","variant of   Starks  ."]},{"name":"Sturkie","meanings":["Possibly English: variant of   Starkey  ."]},{"name":"Starkie","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Starkey  ."]},{"name":"Sturkey","meanings":["English: possibly a variant of   Starkey  ."]},{"name":"Stark","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire) and English: nickname from Middle English <i>stark</i> ‘strong, sturdy; harsh, severe’ (Old English <i>stearc</i>).","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname for a strong, bold person, from Middle High German <i>stark(e)</i>, German <i>stark</i> ‘strong, brave’.","Czech and Slovak (<b>Štark</b>): of German origin (see 2 above)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Annore Starkey was born about 1205, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Sir Richard Starkey, Baron of Stratton in 1219, in Stretton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died in Stretton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1205–":"umbes 1205–Surnud","1201–1271":"1201–1271","1230–1286":"1230–1286","1232–1338":"1232–1338","1233–Male":"1233–Surnud","1234–Male":"1234–Surnud","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","Abt 1205":"umbes 1205","1286":"1286","1230":"1230","abt. 1234":"umbes 1234","1271":"1271","abt 1232":"umbes 1232","abt. 1230":"umbes 1230","1338":"1338","1205":"1205","Abt 1233":"umbes 1233","1234":"1234","1201":"1201","1233":"1233","1232":"1232","1219":"1219","Stretton, Warrington Unitary authority, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stretton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",", , Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stretton, Cheshire, England":"Stretton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom